Thread:
C++ introduced thread in C++11. It is a unit of execution within a process. A process can have multiple threads, which share the same memory space but can execute independently.

Process:
A process is an independent program in execution.
A process has its own memory and system resources. It is isolated from other processes, meaning that one process cannot directly access the memory of another process. Each process has its own address space, file descriptors, and other resources.

Threads:
A thread is a lightweight unit of execution inside a process.
Multiple threads can exist within the same process and share the same memory and resources, but they can execute independently. Threads are often used to perform tasks concurrently, allowing for better performance and responsiveness in applications.
In C++, you can create and manage threads using the `<thread>` library.

thread t(work);
t.join();

join():
join() is a member function of the thread class is used to ensure that the main thread waits for the worker thread to complete its execution before proceeding with the rest of the program.

join() blocks the calling thread until the worker thread finishes its execution ensuring safe synchronization and resource cleanup.
**Double join() on the same thread will lead to a runtime error.**
**If needed we should check thread is joinable before joining using joinable function.**

t.detach();
detach():
detach() is a member function of the thread class that allows a thread to run independently in the background without the main thread waiting for it to finish.
--> You can no longer use join() to wait for it. 
--> Always check if the thread is joinable before detaching using joinable function.
--> Detaching a thread means that it will continue to run even if the main thread finishes or exits. 
**It is important to ensure that the detached thread does not access any resources that may be destroyed when the main thread exits, as this can lead to undefined behavior.**
--> Detaching a thread is useful for tasks that do not require synchronization with the main thread and can run independently.

Eg: 
Use detach() for a thread that performs a background task, such as logging, where the main thread does not need to wait for its completion.

terminate() is automatically called in destructor if thread is joinable when we don't call join() or detach() on a thread object. When a thread is terminated using terminate(), it will stop executing immediately, and any resources it was using will be released.

1) Ways to Thread Creation:
